"from the accretion disk on scales of about ∼ 0.01 parsec
(typical for the Seyfert galaxies category of AGN) lies the
broad line region (BLR) that produces the line emission. The
UV/optical continuum from the accretion disk photoionizes
the gas clouds in the BLR, and as these gas clouds are sit-
uated deep within the potential well of the black hole, the
emission lines from them are broadened by few thousands of
km/sec. The BLR is surrounded by the dusty torus which
is responsible for the different manifestations of the AGN
when viewed at different orientations (Antonucci 1993; Urry
& Padovani 1995). According to Barvainis (1987), the bump
or excess in the near infrared (NIR) continuum is thermally
produced by the hot dust grains heated by the UV/optical
radiation from the central region. For a typical UV luminos-"
